k from, the levels of radioactive waste from a ground launch will be horrendous. Fission bombs are far less clean than modern fusion devices for a start. Then there is the size of the Orion. The 60's model was small. The smaller the Orion the smaller the pulse units. The smaller the pulse units the less efficient they are.<br>
I think a modern program would be completely different. I would be very much interested in seeing the results of a feasibility study into a large Orion with research focused on ways to reduce fallout. I think it could be a positive result but we will never know unless we do it. <br>
Launching site alone would make a huge difference. Most of the fallout, probably 99%, is from the groundburst. Radiation needs something material to carry it. The mountain of dust being sucked through the fireball could be avoided by a sealaunch. I'm wondering if launching from a Polar region might not be even better. Little atmospheric dust or water vapour to contaminate. No immediate threat to life. After launch the local temperature would quickly freeze much of the atmospheric vapour from melted ice. The area could be cleaned up if necessary and residual fallout would disperse to below background levels. Depending on how clever the researchers were there should be little in the way of irradiated bomb fragments or other matter.<br>
No serious research has ever been conducted into cleaner fission triggers. Clean ones yes but not cleaner. Hydrogen bombs have only been used for weapons and perhaps some limited demolition work in Russia. Experimentation with short lived radioactive isotopes might be a good idea. Something which could be made an put into pulse devices just prior to launch but has such a short half-life it is gone within hours. Special pulse units are only necessary for the very brief atmospheric stage after all. Once in space you can use any old pulse unit. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

