p://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Math.</span><hr size=1> On what do you base that prediction? If you are using the outdated system of linear scale determination then that figure will be wrong. Hormesis indicates that low amounts of radiation are harmless and an increase of even 300% in World levels would if anything be beneficial. Reducing cancer rates globally.<br>
A modern Orion with pulse units designed specifically for low fallout and atmospheric stage spaceflight applications wouldn't release nearly as much radiation as the 1950's models. Design of atomic devices is more of an art than a science. <br>
The Taylor Dyson fission pulse design would have undoubtedly created a lot of radiation but I question the prediction on medical grounds. Be very interested in knowing who you relied on for data about human toxicity levels. The US regulatory body has always taken the view that any degree of radiation is harmful and that simply isn't true. Using that as a basis for predicting 20 deaths globally would be misleading. <br>
Just like saying 200 degree temperatures will kill you and therefore 20 degrees must also be damaging. On a linear scale it would be 10% as damaging. Completely false but this is how radiation tolerance levels are calculated. <br>
If you calculated 20 deaths using this system then the truth is that the real answer is likely a net gain. The hormetic effect would mean less cancers globally and fewer deaths around the world than might otherwise have been expected. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/24/02 8:08:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=69.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Math.</span><hr size=1> It's not a linear scale... It's rather complex, but my evidence for such was as directly quoted from George Dyson's book Project Orion. It's not all positive in there, and actually turns fairly negitive the more you go along, with stuff like the pusher plates, most of the scientists bailing on the idea, etc. Freeman Dyson would not build an Orion, and it's in question if Ted Taylor would build one. Most of the other scientists feel similar. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 381<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/24/02 8:50:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=69.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=